        <!-- Objectives of Cybersecurity Awareness Section -->
        <div class="row mt-5">
            <div class="col-md-12">
                <h3>Objectives of Cybersecurity Awareness</h3>
                <p>1. Phishing and Social Engineering:</strong> Teaching employees to recognize and avoid deceptive emails, messages, or websites designed to trick them into revealing sensitive information. Raising awareness about tactics cybercriminals use to manipulate individuals into divulging confidential data.</p>
                <p>2. Password Security:</strong> Educating employees on creating strong, unique passwords and the importance of regularly updating them. Promoting the use of MFA (multi-factor authentication) to enhance account security by requiring multiple forms of verification.</p>
                <p>3. Data Protection and the GDPR:</strong> Explaining the principles of the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) and its implications for handling personal data. Training on secure data handling practices, including encryption and data minimization.</p>
                <p>4. Mobile and Remote Security:</strong> Addressing security challenges related to smartphones, tablets, and other mobile devices and providing guidelines for securing remote work environments.</p>
                <p>5. Reporting Incidents:</strong> Encouraging employees to promptly report suspicious activities or security incidents to appropriate channels.</p>
                <p>6. Safe Use of Social Media:</strong> Educating employees about the risks of social media usage, such as oversharing and social engineering attempts, and managing their digital footprint.</p>
                <p>7. Physical Security (Tailgating and Clear Desk):</strong> Teaching employees to prevent unauthorized physical access to facilities and promoting the importance of clearing desks of sensitive information to prevent data breaches.</p>
                <p>8. Data Classification:</strong> Explaining how to categorize data based on its sensitivity and the appropriate handling procedures for each classification.</p>
                <p>9. Supply Chain and Third-Party Risk:</strong> Understanding potential cybersecurity risks associated with third-party vendors and suppliers, and supplying targeted training to external partners to maintain security standards.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

